Here is the step-by-step guide to setting up your Git repository, hosting it on Render, 
and configuring the automated deployment pipeline using a Git Bash environment.

---

## Part 1: Local Git Setup & First Commit

Open **Git Bash** and run the following commands:

```bash
# 1. Create a new directory and navigate into it
mkdir my-render-site && cd my-render-site

# 2. Initialize a local Git repository
git init

# 3. Create the index.html file with the required text
echo "<h1>Site is under construction</h1>" > index.html

# 4. Stage and commit the file
git add index.html
git commit -m "Initial commit: Site under construction"

```

---

## Part 2: Push Code to GitHub

1. Go to [GitHub](https://github.com/) and log in.
2. Click the **New** button to create a new repository.
3. Name your repository (e.g., `my-render-site`). Leave it **Public** and **do not** initialize it with a README or .gitignore. Click **Create repository**.
4. Copy the commands under the section *"…or push an existing repository from the command line"*. It will look like this in your Git Bash:

```bash
# Rename your default branch to main
git branch -M main

# Link your local repository to GitHub (Replace with YOUR actual GitHub URL)
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/my-render-site.git

# Push the code
git push -u origin main

```

---

## Part 3: Deploy to Render

1. Go to [Render Dashboard](https://dashboard.render.com/) and log in (signing in with your GitHub account is recommended).
2. Click **New +** and select **Static Site**.
3. Connect your GitHub account if you haven't already. Under **Connect a repository**, find your `my-render-site` repository and click **Connect**.
4. Give your site a unique name.
5. Leave the default settings as they are:
* **Branch:** `main`
* **Build Command:** *(Leave blank)*
* **Publish directory:** `.` (or leave blank for the root directory)


6. Scroll down and click **Deploy Static Site**.

Once the deployment finishes, Render will provide you with a live URL (e.g., `https://my-render-site.onrender.com`). Visit it to verify it displays **"Site is under construction"**.

---

## Part 4: Configure Render Webhook on GitHub

While Render automatically deploys GitHub commits by default if you connected your account, setting up an explicit build webhook ensures your pipeline triggers correctly across decoupled workflows.

1. On your Render static site dashboard, go to the **Settings** tab.
2. Scroll down to the **Deploy Hook** section and copy the **Deploy Hook URL**.
3. Go back to your repository on **GitHub**.
4. Click on **Settings** -> **Webhooks** -> **Add webhook**.
5. Paste the Render Deploy Hook URL into the **Payload URL** field.
6. Set **Content type** to `application/json`.
7. Leave the rest as default ("Just the push event") and click **Add webhook**.

---

## Part 5: Update & Verify the Automatic Pipeline

Now, update your code locally and let the pipeline push changes automatically.

```bash
# 1. Update index.html with your Name and PRN (Replace placeholders)
echo "<h1>Name: Your Name</h1><h2>PRN: Your PRN Number</h2>" > index.html

# 2. Stage the changes
git add index.html

# 3. Commit the changes
git commit -m "Update: Added name and PRN"

# 4. Push to GitHub
git push origin main

```

### Verification

1. Head back to your **Render Dashboard**. You will notice a new build has automatically triggered and says *“In progress”* followed by *“Live”*.
2. Refresh your Render website URL.
3. Your updated webpage will now automatically display your **Name** and **PRN**, confirming that your CI/CD deployment pipeline is working perfectly.
